{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TfVzf1kNpFb9kDDHEvWvKb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01AgkwwNTLXFG4CNkV5GhUrg","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/tmp/findings.txt","content":"================================================================\nRABBITMQ CLUSTER COMPLIANCE AUDIT — READ-ONLY FINDINGS\n================================================================\nAudit Date : 2026-06-16\nNamespace  : karma-rabbitmq-maximal-lifecycle-roll-0f5d4e03-cluster-a\nAuditor    : automated read-only inspection (no cluster changes made)\n\n================================================================\n1. CLUSTER HEALTH & TOPOLOGY\n================================================================\nNodes (3 / 3 Running, all disk nodes, no RAM-only nodes):\n  - rabbit@rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n  - rabbit@rabbitmq-1.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n  - rabbit@rabbitmq-2.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n\nRabbitMQ Version : 3.12.14  [WARNING: release series marked OUT OF SUPPORT]\nErlang Version   : 25.3.2.15 (OTP 25)\nUptime (node-0)  : ~594 seconds at time of audit\nAlarms           : none\nNetwork Partitions : none\nMaintenance Mode : all nodes — not under maintenance\nCluster Partition Handling : pause_minority  [COMPLIANT — safe for 3-node]\n\nMemory (node-0):\n  Total used : ~0.19 GB\n  High watermark : 0.4 × available RAM (67.5 GB computed)\n  Queue count : 2\n  Connection count : 0 (no active client connections at audit time)\n\nDisk:\n  Free disk space : 1037.2 GB\n  Low watermark   : 0.05 GB\n\n================================================================\n2. VIRTUAL HOSTS\n================================================================\nName   | Description         | Default Queue Type\n-------+---------------------+--------------------\n/      | Default virtual host | undefined (classic)\n/app   | (none)              | undefined (classic)\n/ops   | (none)              | undefined (classic)\n\n[NOTE] The default vhost \"/\" has no client permissions except for \"admin\".\n       Custom vhosts /app and /ops isolate workloads appropriately.\n[NOTE] No vhost descriptions set for /app and /ops — minor documentation gap.\n\n================================================================\n3. USERS & TAGS\n================================================================\nUser      | Tags\n----------+--------------\nadmin     | administrator\napp-user  | management\nops-user  | management\n\n[NOTE] Three users defined; no guest account usage (loopback_users.guest = false\n       is set in configuration, preventing default guest login from the network).\n[CONCERN] The built-in \"guest\" user status could not be verified via\n          rabbitmqctl list_users — it does not appear, suggesting it may have\n          been deleted or is still present with default password. Recommend\n          confirming guest user is deleted or password-changed.\n[NOTE] \"admin\" holds full administrator tag. app-user and ops-user hold only\n       \"management\" (management UI access, no admin operations).\n\n================================================================\n4. USER PERMISSIONS (per vhost)\n================================================================\nVhost  | User      | Configure | Write | Read\n-------+-----------+-----------+-------+------\n/app   | admin     | .*        | .*    | .*\n/app   | app-user  | .*        | .*    | .*\n/ops   | admin     | .*        | .*    | .*\n/ops   | ops-user  | .*        | .*    | .*\n/      | admin     | .*        | .*    | .*\n\n[CONCERN] app-user has full configure+write+read on /app (pattern \".*\").\n          This grants the app account the ability to declare/delete any queue\n          or exchange. If the app only needs to publish/consume from known\n          queues, tighter configure permissions (e.g., \"^$\" or specific names)\n          are recommended to reduce blast radius.\n[CONCERN] ops-user has full configure+write+read on /ops — same recommendation.\n[NOTE] Cross-vhost access is correctly restricted: app-user has no permissions\n       on /ops or /, and ops-user has no permissions on /app or /.\n[NOTE] The default \"/\" vhost is accessible only to admin — appropriate.\n\n================================================================\n5. POLICIES\n================================================================\nVhost /app:\n  Name    : ha-all\n  Pattern : .* (applies to ALL queues in /app)\n  Apply-to: queues\n  Definition: {\"ha-mode\":\"all\",\"ha-sync-mode\":\"automatic\"}\n  Priority: 0\n\nVhost /ops: (no policies defined)\nVhost /   : (no policies defined)\n\n[WARNING] The \"ha-all\" policy uses classic HA mirroring (ha-mode=all). This\n          is a DEPRECATED feature as of RabbitMQ 3.8 and has been removed in\n          RabbitMQ 4.x. The recommended replacement is Quorum Queues.\n          ha-mode=all replicates to every node which can increase write latency\n          and does not offer the durability guarantees of the Raft-based quorum\n          queue implementation.\n[NOTE] ha-sync-mode=automatic ensures mirrors sync immediately on join, which\n       is the safer setting (vs. manual sync which can leave mirrors stale).\n[NOTE] /ops has no HA/quorum policy — ops-queue has no replication configured.\n\n================================================================\n6. QUEUES\n================================================================\nVhost /app:\n  Name      : app-queue\n  Type      : classic\n  Durable   : true\n  Auto-del  : false\n  Arguments : x-queue-type=classic\n  Policy    : ha-all (HA mirroring all nodes)\n  State     : running\n  Consumers : 0  [NOTE: no active consumers at audit time]\n  Messages  : 1882 ready, 0 unacknowledged\n  [NOTE] 1882 messages are queued with 0 consumers — possible backlog or\n         consumer outage (app-producer pod is in CrashLoopBackOff; see §9).\n\nVhost /ops:\n  Name      : ops-queue\n  Type      : classic\n  Durable   : true\n  Auto-del  : false\n  Arguments : x-queue-type=classic\n  Policy    : (none)\n  State     : running\n  Consumers : 0\n  Messages  : 0 ready, 0 unacknowledged\n\n[WARNING] Both queues use the classic type. See §5 warning on deprecation of\n          classic HA mirroring. Quorum queues provide stronger consistency\n          guarantees and are the current recommended durable queue type.\n\n================================================================\n7. TLS / ENCRYPTION SETTINGS\n================================================================\nTLS Listeners:\n  AMQP plaintext : 0.0.0.0:5672   [WARNING — see below]\n  AMQP over TLS  : 0.0.0.0:5671\n  Management HTTP: [::]:15672      (plaintext)\n  Prometheus     : 0.0.0.0:15692  (plaintext)\n  Clustering     : [::]:25672\n\nTLS Configuration:\n  CA Certificate  : /etc/rabbitmq/tls/ca.crt\n  Server Cert     : /etc/rabbitmq/tls/tls.crt\n  Server Key      : /etc/rabbitmq/tls/tls.key\n  Verify Mode     : verify_peer\n  Fail if no peer cert: false\n\nTLS Certificate Details:\n  Issuer    : CN=rabbitmq-ca (self-signed CA)\n  Subject   : CN=rabbitmq\n  Valid From: 2026-06-16\n  Valid Until: 2026-09-14 (~90 days from audit date)\n  Signature : SHA-256 with RSA\n  Key Size  : 2048-bit RSA\n  SANs      : covers all rabbitmq and rabbitmq-headless DNS names for this\n              namespace plus each individual pod FQDN\n\nCA Certificate:\n  Issuer    : CN=rabbitmq-ca (self-signed)\n  Valid Until: 2028-06-15 (2 years)\n  Signature : SHA-256 with RSA\n\n[WARNING] fail_if_no_peer_cert = false — TLS client certificate authentication\n          is not enforced. Clients can connect over TLS without presenting a\n          certificate, relying only on password-based auth.\n[WARNING] AMQP plaintext port 5672 remains open alongside TLS port 5671.\n          Clients can bypass TLS entirely. Recommend disabling plaintext port\n          unless there is a documented operational need.\n[WARNING] Management API (port 15672) and Prometheus (15692) run over plain\n          HTTP — credentials and metrics are transmitted in cleartext within\n          the cluster network.\n[NOTE] 2048-bit RSA is currently acceptable but 4096-bit or ECDSA (P-256/P-384)\n       is recommended for new deployments.\n[NOTE] Server cert expires 2026-09-14 — approximately 90 days. Ensure rotation\n       is planned before expiry.\n\n================================================================\n8. ENABLED PLUGINS\n================================================================\n  rabbitmq_management        — management UI + HTTP API (port 15672)\n  rabbitmq_management_agent  — per-node management data collection\n  rabbitmq_prometheus        — Prometheus metrics exporter (port 15692)\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s — Kubernetes-native peer discovery\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_common\n  rabbitmq_web_dispatch\n  amqp_client\n  cowboy / cowlib / accept / prometheus\n\n[NOTE] No shovel, federation, or LDAP plugins enabled — attack surface is\n       minimal and appropriate for this use case.\n\n================================================================\n9. KUBERNETES WORKLOAD STATUS\n================================================================\nPod Status at time of audit:\n  rabbitmq-0            Running     (9m uptime)\n  rabbitmq-1            Running     (10m uptime)\n  rabbitmq-2            Running     (11m uptime)\n  app-client            Running     (1 restart)\n  app-producer          CrashLoopBackOff  [ALERT — see below]\n  ops-client            Running\n  prometheus            Running\n  curl-test             Running\n  openssl-toolbox       Running\n  rabbitmq-setup        Completed   (setup job succeeded)\n\n[ALERT] app-producer is in CrashLoopBackOff with multiple restarts. This\n        explains the 1882 unacknowledged messages in app-queue with 0 consumers.\n        The message backlog will grow indefinitely until the producer is fixed or\n        the queue TTL/length limit policy is applied.\n\nContainer Image:\n  rabbitmq:3.12-management (floating tag — not pinned to a digest)\n[CONCERN] Using a floating image tag (3.12-management) means pod restarts may\n          pull a different image version than currently running. Pin to a\n          specific digest for reproducibility.\n\nSecurity Context:\n  Pod securityContext : {} (not set — running as default container user)\n  Container resources : {} (no CPU/memory limits set)\n[CONCERN] No resource requests/limits on RabbitMQ containers — risk of node\n          resource starvation. No security context hardening (runAsNonRoot,\n          readOnlyRootFilesystem, seccompProfile) is applied.\n\nNetwork Policies: NONE defined in namespace.\n[CONCERN] No Kubernetes NetworkPolicy restricts pod-to-pod traffic. Any pod\n          in the cluster can reach RabbitMQ on ports 5672, 15672, etc.\n\nRBAC:\n  ServiceAccount: rabbitmq\n  Role: rabbitmq-peer-discovery\n    Permissions: get/list/watch on endpoints and pods\n  [NOTE] RBAC scope is appropriately minimal — read-only access to endpoints\n         and pods only, scoped to the namespace. No cluster-wide roles.\n\n================================================================\n10. AUTHENTICATION & SECURITY CONFIGURATION\n================================================================\nAuth Backends  : rabbit_auth_backend_internal (local users only — no LDAP/external)\nAuth Mechanisms: PLAIN, AMQPLAIN\nloopback_users.guest = false  (guest cannot login from non-loopback)\n\n[CONCERN] PLAIN and AMQPLAIN transmit credentials in base64 (effectively\n          cleartext). Since plaintext port 5672 is open, credentials could be\n          intercepted. Enforce TLS-only and consider adding EXTERNAL mechanism\n          (mutual TLS) for service accounts.\n[NOTE] No LDAP or external auth integration — all credentials are stored\n       locally in the RabbitMQ internal database.\n\n================================================================\n11. OPERATOR POLICIES & GLOBAL PARAMETERS\n================================================================\nOperator Policies : none\nGlobal Parameters :\n  internal_cluster_id = \"rabbitmq-cluster-id-bRVVpwxhUfLpqhg641nh3g\"\n\n[NOTE] No operator policy overrides. The ha-all policy in /app is a regular\n       (non-operator) policy and can be modified by any administrator.\n\n================================================================\n12. FEATURE FLAGS\n================================================================\nAll relevant feature flags are ENABLED, including:\n  quorum_queue, stream_queue, virtual_host_metadata,\n  user_limits, maintenance_mode_status, feature_flags_v2,\n  classic_mirrored_queue_version, classic_queue_type_delivery_support\n\n[NOTE] quorum_queue and stream_queue features are enabled but unused —\n       current queues are classic type. Migration to quorum queues is\n       possible without a flag change.\n\n================================================================\nSUMMARY OF FINDINGS\n================================================================\nCRITICAL / ALERT:\n  [1] app-producer pod in CrashLoopBackOff — 1882 messages undelivered in app-queue.\n\nHIGH RISK:\n  [2] RabbitMQ 3.12.x is OUT OF SUPPORT — no further security patches.\n  [3] Plaintext AMQP port 5672 open — TLS bypass possible.\n  [4] fail_if_no_peer_cert=false — client cert auth not enforced.\n  [5] Classic HA mirroring (ha-all policy) is deprecated; should migrate to quorum queues.\n  [6] No NetworkPolicy — unrestricted pod-to-cluster access to RabbitMQ ports.\n\nMEDIUM RISK:\n  [7] app-user and ops-user have full configure (.*) permissions — over-privileged.\n  [8] Management API (15672) and Prometheus (15692) served over plain HTTP.\n  [9] No CPU/memory resource limits on RabbitMQ pods.\n  [10] Pod securityContext not hardened (no runAsNonRoot, no seccomp).\n  [11] Floating image tag (rabbitmq:3.12-management) — not pinned to digest.\n\nLOW RISK / INFORMATIONAL:\n  [12] Server TLS cert expires 2026-09-14 (~90 days) — plan rotation.\n  [13] 2048-bit RSA key — acceptable now, but 4096-bit or ECDSA preferred.\n  [14] CA is self-signed (CN=rabbitmq-ca) — not from a trusted public CA.\n  [15] PLAIN/AMQPLAIN auth mechanisms used — no mutual TLS for service accounts.\n  [16] No vhost descriptions on /app and /ops.\n  [17] ops-queue has no replication policy (no HA/quorum configured).\n\nNO ACTION REQUIRED:\n  - Cluster heartbeat timeout (60s) is appropriate for 3-node cluster.\n  - pause_minority partition handling is correct for 3 nodes.\n  - RBAC is appropriately minimal (read-only endpoints/pods).\n  - No operator policies override user-set policies (acceptable).\n  - All 3 nodes running; no alarms or partitions detected.\n\n================================================================\nEND OF AUDIT REPORT\n================================================================\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":425,"cache_read_input_tokens":42171,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":425},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5d945cf1-8e1a-4f38-8675-a541e1b722a5","uuid":"ae115630-eddc-4fa4-a99a-08545b07f2db","request_id":"req_011Cc7727d5RSeLFrBDEEesE"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AgkwwNTLXFG4CNkV5GhUrg","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /tmp/findings.txt (file state is current in your context — no need to Read it back)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5d945cf1-8e1a-4f38-8675-a541e1b722a5","uuid":"5483b09b-65de-4e7c-a67a-3ade252517c1","timestamp":"2026-06-16T14:35:47.792Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/tmp/findings.txt","content":"================================================================\nRABBITMQ CLUSTER COMPLIANCE AUDIT — READ-ONLY FINDINGS\n================================================================\nAudit Date : 2026-06-16\nNamespace  : karma-rabbitmq-maximal-lifecycle-roll-0f5d4e03-cluster-a\nAuditor    : automated read-only inspection (no cluster changes made)\n\n================================================================\n1. CLUSTER HEALTH & TOPOLOGY\n================================================================\nNodes (3 / 3 Running, all disk nodes, no RAM-only nodes):\n  - rabbit@rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n  - rabbit@rabbitmq-1.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n  - rabbit@rabbitmq-2.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n\nRabbitMQ Version : 3.12.14  [WARNING: release series marked OUT OF SUPPORT]\nErlang Version   : 25.3.2.15 (OTP 25)\nUptime (node-0)  : ~594 seconds at time of audit\nAlarms           : none\nNetwork Partitions : none\nMaintenance Mode : all nodes — not under maintenance\nCluster Partition Handling : pause_minority  [COMPLIANT — safe for 3-node]\n\nMemory (node-0):\n  Total used : ~0.19 GB\n  High watermark : 0.4 × available RAM (67.5 GB computed)\n  Queue count : 2\n  Connection count : 0 (no active client connections at audit time)\n\nDisk:\n  Free disk space : 1037.2 GB\n  Low watermark   : 0.05 GB\n\n================================================================\n2. VIRTUAL HOSTS\n================================================================\nName   | Description         | Default Queue Type\n-------+---------------------+--------------------\n/      | Default virtual host | undefined (classic)\n/app   | (none)              | undefined (classic)\n/ops   | (none)              | undefined (classic)\n\n[NOTE] The default vhost \"/\" has no client permissions except for \"admin\".\n       Custom vhosts /app and /ops isolate workloads appropriately.\n[NOTE] No vhost descriptions set for /app and /ops — minor documentation gap.\n\n================================================================\n3. USERS & TAGS\n================================================================\nUser      | Tags\n----------+--------------\nadmin     | administrator\napp-user  | management\nops-user  | management\n\n[NOTE] Three users defined; no guest account usage (loopback_users.guest = false\n       is set in configuration, preventing default guest login from the network).\n[CONCERN] The built-in \"guest\" user status could not be verified via\n          rabbitmqctl list_users — it does not appear, suggesting it may have\n          been deleted or is still present with default password. Recommend\n          confirming guest user is deleted or password-changed.\n[NOTE] \"admin\" holds full administrator tag. app-user and ops-user hold only\n       \"management\" (management UI access, no admin operations).\n\n================================================================\n4. USER PERMISSIONS (per vhost)\n================================================================\nVhost  | User      | Configure | Write | Read\n-------+-----------+-----------+-------+------\n/app   | admin     | .*        | .*    | .*\n/app   | app-user  | .*        | .*    | .*\n/ops   | admin     | .*        | .*    | .*\n/ops   | ops-user  | .*        | .*    | .*\n/      | admin     | .*        | .*    | .*\n\n[CONCERN] app-user has full configure+write+read on /app (pattern \".*\").\n          This grants the app account the ability to declare/delete any queue\n          or exchange. If the app only needs to publish/consume from known\n          queues, tighter configure permissions (e.g., \"^$\" or specific names)\n          are recommended to reduce blast radius.\n[CONCERN] ops-user has full configure+write+read on /ops — same recommendation.\n[NOTE] Cross-vhost access is correctly restricted: app-user has no permissions\n       on /ops or /, and ops-user has no permissions on /app or /.\n[NOTE] The default \"/\" vhost is accessible only to admin — appropriate.\n\n================================================================\n5. POLICIES\n================================================================\nVhost /app:\n  Name    : ha-all\n  Pattern : .* (applies to ALL queues in /app)\n  Apply-to: queues\n  Definition: {\"ha-mode\":\"all\",\"ha-sync-mode\":\"automatic\"}\n  Priority: 0\n\nVhost /ops: (no policies defined)\nVhost /   : (no policies defined)\n\n[WARNING] The \"ha-all\" policy uses classic HA mirroring (ha-mode=all). This\n          is a DEPRECATED feature as of RabbitMQ 3.8 and has been removed in\n          RabbitMQ 4.x. The recommended replacement is Quorum Queues.\n          ha-mode=all replicates to every node which can increase write latency\n          and does not offer the durability guarantees of the Raft-based quorum\n          queue implementation.\n[NOTE] ha-sync-mode=automatic ensures mirrors sync immediately on join, which\n       is the safer setting (vs. manual sync which can leave mirrors stale).\n[NOTE] /ops has no HA/quorum policy — ops-queue has no replication configured.\n\n================================================================\n6. QUEUES\n================================================================\nVhost /app:\n  Name      : app-queue\n  Type      : classic\n  Durable   : true\n  Auto-del  : false\n  Arguments : x-queue-type=classic\n  Policy    : ha-all (HA mirroring all nodes)\n  State     : running\n  Consumers : 0  [NOTE: no active consumers at audit time]\n  Messages  : 1882 ready, 0 unacknowledged\n  [NOTE] 1882 messages are queued with 0 consumers — possible backlog or\n         consumer outage (app-producer pod is in CrashLoopBackOff; see §9).\n\nVhost /ops:\n  Name      : ops-queue\n  Type      : classic\n  Durable   : true\n  Auto-del  : false\n  Arguments : x-queue-type=classic\n  Policy    : (none)\n  State     : running\n  Consumers : 0\n  Messages  : 0 ready, 0 unacknowledged\n\n[WARNING] Both queues use the classic type. See §5 warning on deprecation of\n          classic HA mirroring. Quorum queues provide stronger consistency\n          guarantees and are the current recommended durable queue type.\n\n================================================================\n7. TLS / ENCRYPTION SETTINGS\n================================================================\nTLS Listeners:\n  AMQP plaintext : 0.0.0.0:5672   [WARNING — see below]\n  AMQP over TLS  : 0.0.0.0:5671\n  Management HTTP: [::]:15672      (plaintext)\n  Prometheus     : 0.0.0.0:15692  (plaintext)\n  Clustering     : [::]:25672\n\nTLS Configuration:\n  CA Certificate  : /etc/rabbitmq/tls/ca.crt\n  Server Cert     : /etc/rabbitmq/tls/tls.crt\n  Server Key      : /etc/rabbitmq/tls/tls.key\n  Verify Mode     : verify_peer\n  Fail if no peer cert: false\n\nTLS Certificate Details:\n  Issuer    : CN=rabbitmq-ca (self-signed CA)\n  Subject   : CN=rabbitmq\n  Valid From: 2026-06-16\n  Valid Until: 2026-09-14 (~90 days from audit date)\n  Signature : SHA-256 with RSA\n  Key Size  : 2048-bit RSA\n  SANs      : covers all rabbitmq and rabbitmq-headless DNS names for this\n              namespace plus each individual pod FQDN\n\nCA Certificate:\n  Issuer    : CN=rabbitmq-ca (self-signed)\n  Valid Until: 2028-06-15 (2 years)\n  Signature : SHA-256 with RSA\n\n[WARNING] fail_if_no_peer_cert = false — TLS client certificate authentication\n          is not enforced. Clients can connect over TLS without presenting a\n          certificate, relying only on password-based auth.\n[WARNING] AMQP plaintext port 5672 remains open alongside TLS port 5671.\n          Clients can bypass TLS entirely. Recommend disabling plaintext port\n          unless there is a documented operational need.\n[WARNING] Management API (port 15672) and Prometheus (15692) run over plain\n          HTTP — credentials and metrics are transmitted in cleartext within\n          the cluster network.\n[NOTE] 2048-bit RSA is currently acceptable but 4096-bit or ECDSA (P-256/P-384)\n       is recommended for new deployments.\n[NOTE] Server cert expires 2026-09-14 — approximately 90 days. Ensure rotation\n       is planned before expiry.\n\n================================================================\n8. ENABLED PLUGINS\n================================================================\n  rabbitmq_management        — management UI + HTTP API (port 15672)\n  rabbitmq_management_agent  — per-node management data collection\n  rabbitmq_prometheus        — Prometheus metrics exporter (port 15692)\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s — Kubernetes-native peer discovery\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_common\n  rabbitmq_web_dispatch\n  amqp_client\n  cowboy / cowlib / accept / prometheus\n\n[NOTE] No shovel, federation, or LDAP plugins enabled — attack surface is\n       minimal and appropriate for this use case.\n\n================================================================\n9. KUBERNETES WORKLOAD STATUS\n================================================================\nPod Status at time of audit:\n  rabbitmq-0            Running     (9m uptime)\n  rabbitmq-1            Running     (10m uptime)\n  rabbitmq-2            Running     (11m uptime)\n  app-client            Running     (1 restart)\n  app-producer          CrashLoopBackOff  [ALERT — see below]\n  ops-client            Running\n  prometheus            Running\n  curl-test             Running\n  openssl-toolbox       Running\n  rabbitmq-setup        Completed   (setup job succeeded)\n\n[ALERT] app-producer is in CrashLoopBackOff with multiple restarts. This\n        explains the 1882 unacknowledged messages in app-queue with 0 consumers.\n        The message backlog will grow indefinitely until the producer is fixed or\n        the queue TTL/length limit policy is applied.\n\nContainer Image:\n  rabbitmq:3.12-management (floating tag — not pinned to a digest)\n[CONCERN] Using a floating image tag (3.12-management) means pod restarts may\n          pull a different image version than currently running. Pin to a\n          specific digest for reproducibility.\n\nSecurity Context:\n  Pod securityContext : {} (not set — running as default container user)\n  Container resources : {} (no CPU/memory limits set)\n[CONCERN] No resource requests/limits on RabbitMQ containers — risk of node\n          resource starvation. No security context hardening (runAsNonRoot,\n          readOnlyRootFilesystem, seccompProfile) is applied.\n\nNetwork Policies: NONE defined in namespace.\n[CONCERN] No Kubernetes NetworkPolicy restricts pod-to-pod traffic. Any pod\n          in the cluster can reach RabbitMQ on ports 5672, 15672, etc.\n\nRBAC:\n  ServiceAccount: rabbitmq\n  Role: rabbitmq-peer-discovery\n    Permissions: get/list/watch on endpoints and pods\n  [NOTE] RBAC scope is appropriately minimal — read-only access to endpoints\n         and pods only, scoped to the namespace. No cluster-wide roles.\n\n================================================================\n10. AUTHENTICATION & SECURITY CONFIGURATION\n================================================================\nAuth Backends  : rabbit_auth_backend_internal (local users only — no LDAP/external)\nAuth Mechanisms: PLAIN, AMQPLAIN\nloopback_users.guest = false  (guest cannot login from non-loopback)\n\n[CONCERN] PLAIN and AMQPLAIN transmit credentials in base64 (effectively\n          cleartext). Since plaintext port 5672 is open, credentials could be\n          intercepted. Enforce TLS-only and consider adding EXTERNAL mechanism\n          (mutual TLS) for service accounts.\n[NOTE] No LDAP or external auth integration — all credentials are stored\n       locally in the RabbitMQ internal database.\n\n================================================================\n11. OPERATOR POLICIES & GLOBAL PARAMETERS\n================================================================\nOperator Policies : none\nGlobal Parameters :\n  internal_cluster_id = \"rabbitmq-cluster-id-bRVVpwxhUfLpqhg641nh3g\"\n\n[NOTE] No operator policy overrides. The ha-all policy in /app is a regular\n       (non-operator) policy and can be modified by any administrator.\n\n================================================================\n12. FEATURE FLAGS\n================================================================\nAll relevant feature flags are ENABLED, including:\n  quorum_queue, stream_queue, virtual_host_metadata,\n  user_limits, maintenance_mode_status, feature_flags_v2,\n  classic_mirrored_queue_version, classic_queue_type_delivery_support\n\n[NOTE] quorum_queue and stream_queue features are enabled but unused —\n       current queues are classic type. Migration to quorum queues is\n       possible without a flag change.\n\n================================================================\nSUMMARY OF FINDINGS\n================================================================\nCRITICAL / ALERT:\n  [1] app-producer pod in CrashLoopBackOff — 1882 messages undelivered in app-queue.\n\nHIGH RISK:\n  [2] RabbitMQ 3.12.x is OUT OF SUPPORT — no further security patches.\n  [3] Plaintext AMQP port 5672 open — TLS bypass possible.\n  [4] fail_if_no_peer_cert=false — client cert auth not enforced.\n  [5] Classic HA mirroring (ha-all policy) is deprecated; should migrate to quorum queues.\n  [6] No NetworkPolicy — unrestricted pod-to-cluster access to RabbitMQ ports.\n\nMEDIUM RISK:\n  [7] app-user and ops-user have full configure (.*) permissions — over-privileged.\n  [8] Management API (15672) and Prometheus (15692) served over plain HTTP.\n  [9] No CPU/memory resource limits on RabbitMQ pods.\n  [10] Pod securityContext not hardened (no runAsNonRoot, no seccomp).\n  [11] Floating image tag (rabbitmq:3.12-management) — not pinned to digest.\n\nLOW RISK / INFORMATIONAL:\n  [12] Server TLS cert expires 2026-09-14 (~90 days) — plan rotation.\n  [13] 2048-bit RSA key — acceptable now, but 4096-bit or ECDSA preferred.\n  [14] CA is self-signed (CN=rabbitmq-ca) — not from a trusted public CA.\n  [15] PLAIN/AMQPLAIN auth mechanisms used — no mutual TLS for service accounts.\n  [16] No vhost descriptions on /app and /ops.\n  [17] ops-queue has no replication policy (no HA/quorum configured).\n\nNO ACTION REQUIRED:\n  - Cluster heartbeat timeout (60s) is appropriate for 3-node cluster.\n  - pause_minority partition handling is correct for 3 nodes.\n  - RBAC is appropriately minimal (read-only endpoints/pods).\n  - No operator policies override user-set policies (acceptable).\n  - All 3 nodes running; no alarms or partitions detected.\n\n================================================================\nEND OF AUDIT REPORT\n================================================================\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
